column2: [Copy] allows information to be stored for future recall. Click the STEP or TRACK that the user wants to copy and click [copy].  Click [CQ] and [copy] to copy an entire sequence.
column3: [Paste] allows information to be stored for future recall.  Click the STEP or TRACK that the user wants to paste and click [paste].  The STEP GRID changes appearance when information is being stored.
column4: [Save] stores data.  Hold [save] and click a STEP in the STEP GRID in order to store data in the chosen location. In the STEP GRID empty sequences will be UNLIT, saved sequences will be illuminated PINK, the sequence(s) currently playing will be illuminated GREEN.
column5: [Load] readies a sequence for playback.  Hold [load] to select a sequence from the STEP GRID to load.  In the STEP GRID empty sequences will be UNLIT, saved sequences will be illuminated PINK, the sequence(s) currently playing will be illuminated GREEN.
column6: this is a tool used for creating chords. can also assist with the user being able to randomize chords as this can be included in the regeneration process. if no HRM tracks are turned on(0 = OFF) then there is only one midi note able to be filled intot he step when regenerated. if HRM1 and 2 have values those slots will be filled with values during regeneration.
column7: [HRM1] is one of three possible notes to be played simultaneously or strummed successively. Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn the [HRM1] knob up or down the desired number of MIDI semitone steps for the additional note.                         [CHRD] defines the type of chord the user will create - major, minor, etc.                                                                                                                    Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn the [CHRD] knob to select between the different types of chords in the hyperlinked tables. chord chart  chord chart xls
column8: [HRM2] is one of three possible notes to be played simultaneously or strummed successively.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn the [HRM2] knob up or down the desired number of MIDI semitone steps for the additional note.                    [DENS] is Density and determines the amount of notes in a chord.  Turn the knob to select the amount of notes in a chord.  Possible density notes are 0,2,3, 4.  Positive notes indicate an open (two-handed) chord, and negative numbers indicate a closed (one-handed) chord.
column9: [HRM3] is one of three possible notes to be played simultaneously or strummed successively.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn the [HRM3] knob up or down the desired number of MIDI semitone steps for the additional note.  [INVR] can display in both positive and negative values (possibly called bi-polar later).                                          [INVR] is Inversion. It has positive numbers that weight the chord up and negative numbers that weight the chord down.  For example, imagine a chord (C,G,E) being played on a keyboard. [INVR] can change the octave of a single note, such as E, so that they three notes can be played while remaining a C chord.  When the note placed is C3, the chord is major, and the density would be negative 3, three closed.  That means, we have a closed C major chord.  If we set [NVRT] to negative one, the chord on the step is C3E3G3 and it will be moved to C3E3G2.  If -2, the chord was moved to c3e2g2.  If set to -3, c2e2g2.
column10: [STRM] allows the user to play the HRM notes in ascending order when turned to positve value or descending order when turned to a negative value. The higher the number value the more time between the notes.  Turn [STRM] to 0 in order to play all selected notes on the STEP simultaneously.
column12: [ECHO] stands for MIDI Echo.  MIDI Echo allows the user to repeat a note.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [ECHO] to select the amount of time between each repeated note iteration in fractions of a STEP.
column13: [FDBK] stands for MIDI Echo Feedback.  MIDI Echo Feedback allows the user to select the number of times the echo is repeated.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [FDBK] to select the amount of times a note repeats.  Positive numbers display when the user turns [FDBK] to the right.  The sequencr will express normal, synchronized feedback.  Negative numbers display when the user turns [FDBK] to the left.  The sequencer will express rhythmic patterns when the user does this.
column14: [VELO] stands for MIDI Echo Velocity. MIDI Echo Velocity allows the user to control the volume of repeated notes.  Hold  a STEP or TRACK and turn [VELO] to a negative value to decrease the volume of each repeat; a positive value will increase the volume of each repeat.  For example, use a negative value to very vaguely emulate an analog delay.
column15: [NOTE] stands for Midi Echo Note.  MIDI Echo note allows the user to increase or decrease note value of each repeat.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [NOTE]  Choose a positive value to increase note value with each repeat and a negative value to decrease note value with each repeat. The numerical value set by the knob represents semitones.  MAJ represent "major" which would be a pattern of +4 then +3 then +5. MIN represents "minor," which would be a pattern of +3 then +4 then +5. Mm7 represents "major minor 7" which would be a pattern of +4 then +3 then +3 then +2. mM7 represents "minor major 7" which would be a pattern of +3 then +4 then +4 then +1.  MM7 represents "major major 7" which would be a pattern of +4 then +3 then +4 then +1. SUS4 represents "suspended 4" which would be a pattern of +4 then +1 then +2 then +5. SUS2 represents "suspended 2" which would be a pattern of +2 then +5 then +5 then
column17: [sync] allows the user to toggle between different syncronization functions.  Click [sync] and turn the 16 knob editor to chose whether a TRACK will be a LEAD, FLLW, 1SHT.  LEAD (the leader track) forces follower TRACKS to their first STEP when LEAD reaches its first STEP.   It is possible to program multiple LEAD TRACKS.  This is a top down feature.  Everytime the user programs an additional LEAD,  the TRACKS below it are FLLW (follower tracks).    FLLW TRACKS are synchronized with the LEAD.  When the LEAD reaches its first STEP, all FLLW TRACKS are forced to their first STEP.  1SHT allows the user to select a TRACK to play through and restart only when the LEAD reaches its first STEP again.  LEAD will force a 1SHT TRACK to play through once when that LEAD TRACK reaches its first STEP.
column18: [arp] allows the user to play notes in quick succession inside of a single STEP.  Hold TRACK and Click [arp] to toggle on the arpeggiator for all STEPs.  Click [arp] to toggle on the arpeggiator 16 step editor.  While in this mode, press any TRACK to edit STEPS of that TRACK.  The 16 knob editor is used to control direction and timing of all 16 STEPS of a TRACK.  Top set of encoders input "time of arp" per step(1/2 dotted, 1/2triplet, 1/2,  1/4 dotted, 1/4triplet, 1/4, 1/8 dotted, 1/8triplet, 1/8,1/16 dotted, 1/16triplet, 1/16). Bottom encoders set direction of arp(up, down, up/down, random, more from ironsound glitch hero)
column19: [rnge] minimum/maximum range values allow the user to set the minimum and maximum values for NOTE, GATE, VELOCITY, TEMPO, and JITTER. Click [rnge] to toggle values for GATE, VELO, TEMPO, or JITTER.  The 16 knob editor sets the range for mininum and maximum value that TRACKS allow.  When min or max is reached,  these values will wrap around.  HOLD [range] and push encoder to select attribute range to edit per track
column20: [synth] allows the user to edit the internal synthesizer.  Click [synth] to toggle on the synthesizer editing screen.  The screen will now show editing parameters for the synthesizer.  The user can click a TRACK (I-XVI) to select which synthesizer they wish to edit.
column21: Events are placed on steps and effect all steps on that track. example: placing a NOTE EVENT of +3 on STEP 4 of TRACK 1 results in all STEPs on TRACK 1 increasing 3 semitones every time the chaselight crosses STEP 4.  EVENTS will occur on muted steps. but not when the step is toggled off.
column22: [NOTE] stands for Note Event.  A Note Event allows the user to increase or decrease the track in semitones.  These changes are cumulative.  Hold a STEP and turn [NOTE] to select the number of semitones (midi note numbers) the TRACK will increase or decrease when the chaselight crosses a STEP.  The minumum and maximum note value is set by [rnge] and when either is met the value wraps around.
column23: [GATE] stands for Note Gate Length Events.  Note Gate Length Events allow the user to increase or decrease the duration (gate length) of notes in a TRACK.  Gate percentage changes are cumulative. Hold a STEP and turn [GATE] to select the percentage a TRACK will increase or decrease every time the chaselight crosses a STEP.  The minumum and maximum gate length value is set by [rnge], when either is met the value wraps around.
column24: [VELO] stands for Note Velocity Event.  Note Gate Velocity Event allows the user to increase or decrease velocity level of a TRACK. Hold STEP and turn [VELO] to set the value the TRACK will increase or decrease in velocity every time the chaselight crosses the STEP.  The minumum and maximum note value is set by [rnge], when either is met the value wraps around.
column25: [SHFT] stand for Shift Events.  Shift Events allow the user to move attributes of STEPS forward or backward to other STEPS.  Shift attributes forward with positive values or backward with negative values.  Hold a STEP and turn [SHFT] knob to apply this event to a step.  Shift Events do not affect toggled on/off settings.  For example,  on TRACK 1 toggle all odd numbered steps on (all even numbered steps off) to place a shift event of +1 on STEP 1 of same TRACK. This results in all of the attributes except for events and toggle ON/OFF to be moved from the odd numbered steps to the even numbered STEPS and vice versa.  Hold a TRACK and turn [SHFT] to apply what is called MOVE EVENT (text on screen changes to say MOVE). This style of event moves everything including events and toggled on/off settings. These can also be negative or postive values.  This event is applied to the TRACK and always occures on the first STEP of a TRACK. The MOVE EVENT always occures on STEP 1(even if it is skipped)
column26: Events are placed on steps and effect all steps on that track. example: placing a NOTE EVENT of +3 on STEP 4 of TRACK 1 results in all STEPs on TRACK 1 increasing 3 semitones every time the chaselight crosses STEP 4.  EVENTS will occur on muted steps. but not when the step is toggled off.
column27: [BEG] stands for begin events.  Begin events allow the user to move the start point of the TRACK.  Hold a STEP and turn [BEG] to adjust values.  Use a positive value to move the start point forward.  Use a negative value to move the start point backward.  This is cumulative and when reaching the first or last available STEP in the TRACK will wrap around.
column28: [END] stands for End Events.  End Events allow the user move the end point of a TRACK.  Hold  a STEP and turn [END] to adjust values.  Use a positive value to move the end point forward.  Use a negative value move the end point backward.  This is cumulative and when reaching the first or last available STEP in the track will wrap around.
column29: [JUMP] stands for JUMP Events.  JUMP Events allow the user enter a STEP number to jump to after it is played, choose 1-16 to choose the STEP to jump to. this feature is used in conjunction with the LOOP feature in order to create buchla 249e and 250e loop/jump points.  Hold  a STEP and turn [JUMP] to adjust values 1-16.
column30: [LOOP] stands for Loop Events.  Loop Events allow the user enter a number of times the jump event happens, choose 1-16 to choose the amout of times. this feature is used in conjunction with the JUMP feature in order to create buchla 249e and 250e loop/jump points.  Hold  a STEP and turn [LOOP] to adjust values 1-16.
column32: [chan] allows the user to select MIDI channels on TRACKs. click [chan] to use the 16 knob editor to adjust MIDI channel for each TRACK.
column33: [Dir] determines the playback direction of a TRACK.  Hold [dir] and click STEP ONE to select forward playback, STEP TWO selects backward playback, STEP THREE selects ping-pong playback, and STEP FOUR selects random playback.  The user is allowed to select playback direction individually for each TRACK.
column34: [Emit] TRACK allows user to program values to send to receiver tracks.  Hold [emit] and click a track to to enter into an emitter edit mode. The 16 knob editor is used to send values to other TRACKS.  Possible selections are:  NOTE, GATE, VELO, TIME, JITR, GRV.  In this mode, the lower group of knobs are used to select the attributes (NOTE, GATE, VELO, etc...) to edit.
column35: [Rcv] TRACK receives information from an emitter TRACK.  Hold [rcv] while clicking a TRACK to toggle it as a receiver or a non-receiver TRACK.
column37: [regen] randomizes selected attributes of a TRACK.  Hold [regen] and wait for all knobs to illuminate.  The user may click any knob that they do not want [regen] to randomize. Hold [regen] and click a TRACK to randomize it immediately.  Hold [regen] and click the STEP of a TRACK to determine how many times a TRACK plays through completely before randomizing.  Hold [CQ] and click [regen] to use the 16 knob editor to adjust percent of randomization of values from 0% to 100%.  The knobs specifically correspond to tracks.  In this mode, the lower group of knobs are used to select the attributes (NOTE, GATE, VELO, etc...) to edit.
column38: [RMX] only reorganizes the notes toggled on inside of a TRACK. It does not change values on the STEPS.  Hold [RMX] and click a TRACK to remix it immediately.  Hold the [RMX] and click the STEP of a TRACK to determine how many times a TRACK plays through completely before  remixing.
column39: [Breed] blends the attributes of two TRACKS to form a third TRACK. Hold [breed] and click a TRACK to create two parents and a child.  The TRACK clicked will be parent one, and the next TRACK down will be parent two.  The next TRACK down will be the child TRACK. Every attribute in every STEP of the child TRACK will have a 50% probability of inheriting that attribute from one of the parent TRACKS.  This includes STEP on/off toggles.  Hold [breed] while clicking a STEP in either parent TRACK to specify the number of playbacks before a new child is generated.  Parent one will illuminate as red,  parent two will appear as green, and the child will appear as orange.
column40: [FREEZE] immediately stops [REGEN], [RMX], and [BREED]. Click to toggle off/on in order to stop regeneration, remix, and breed immediately.
column42: [SHAPE1] allows the user to select the shape of a wave.  Hold STEP or TRACK and turn [SHAPE1] knob to select a wave shape for the modulator.  Select triangle, ramp, square, saw, or random. A push and turn will skew the shape to the left or right
column43: [MIN] is the start point for the modulator and [MAX] is the end point of the modulator.  Click the knob to toggle between [Min] and [Max]. Turn the knob to select [MIN] and [MAX] from 0-127.  Invert the waveform by beginning [MIN] with the higher number.
column44: [CYCL/STEP] allows the user to toggle between cycles and steps by clicking the knob.  In cycle mode, hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [CYCL] to determine how many times the shape occurs.  For example, "4" would mean the shape would cycle four times on that STEP.  In step mode, hold a STEP and turn [STEP] to determine how many steps the shape will take to cycle once.  For example, if the user holds STEP one and sets it to "4," the shape will complete on STEP four.
column45: [DEST] selects the destination of the modulator. this can be any encoder function of any track or any CC when its is a midi CC the midi channel of the CC is selected by the channel of the sequencer track.
column47: [SHAPE2] allows the user to select the shape of a wave.  Hold STEP or TRACK and turn [SHAPE1] knob to select a wave shape for the modulator.  Select triangle, ramp, square, saw, or random. A push turn will skew the shape the left or the right
column48: [MIN] is the start point for the modulator and [MAX] is the end point of the modulator.  Click the knob to toggle between [Min] and [Max]. Turn the knob to select [MIN] and [MAX] from 0-127.  Invert the waveform by beginning [MIN] with the higher number.
column49: [CYCL/STEP] allows the user to toggle between cycles and steps by clicking the knob.  In cycle mode, hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [CYCL] to determine how many times the shape occurs.  For example, "4" would mean the shape would cycle four times on that STEP.  In step mode, hold a STEP and turn [STEP] to determine how many steps the shape will take to cycle once.  For example, if the user holds STEP one and sets it to "4," the shape will complete on STEP four.
column50: [DEST] selects the destination of the modulator. this can be any encoder function of any track or any CC when its is a midi CC the midi channel of the CC is selected by the channel of the sequencer track.
column52: [slice] divides the TRACK into multiple loops.  Hold [slice] and click a STEP to place a slice in a TRACK.  Place a [slice] on a STEP to create a loop that includes it and STEP numbers above it.  Place a [slice] on a STEP to make it the first STEP in a new loop. It is possible to [slice] a TRACK up to three times for a total of four loops.  This allows multiple chase lights to loop separantely and create miniature loops in the TRACK.  Hold [slice] and click TRACK to toggle [slice] points on/off.
column53: [nest] opens the STEP GRID to allow the user to program a sequence inside of a STEP.  Hold [nest] and click a STEP.  This opens the STEP GRID to allow the user to program a sequence inside of a STEP.  After programming, click [HOME] to escape, the STEP will appear purple and flash when being played.
column54: Click [swap] then click two TRACK buttons and it will "swap" both of them except for the assigned midi channel and emit attributes.
column55: [link] allows the user to  play tracks one after another in order to create tracks with more steps.  Select a set of TRACKS that will play back in sequential order
column57: [NDGE] moves a note slightly before or after the beginning of a STEP.   Hold a STEP and turn [NDGE] to adjust by increments of one on individual STEPS. Hold  a TRACK and turn [NDGE] to apply "swing" this feature goes from swing to "jittering" at higher values.
column58: [PROB] is the probability in percentage that a STEP has of being played every time the sequence loops around.  [PROB] ranges from 0-99 and is based solely on percentage, not condition.  Hold a TRACK and turn [PROB] to adjust.  To toggle between probability (percentage) and conditional (ratio) click [PROB]. Negative numbers are Conditional. -1 should be a high condition, -16 should be a lower condtion,
column59: Hold STEP and turn [GRUV] to choose a [nest] for a particular STEP.  Hold TRACK and turn [GRUV] to place a [nest] on the entire TRACK.  [GRUV] allows the user to use the encoder to scroll through nests they have created.
column60: [SPIN] shifts all TRACK attributes (including on/off toggles) to the the next higher or lower numbered TRACK. Turn [SPIN] left to shift all attributes (except midi channel) one TRACK number lower or higher. Turn [SPIN] right to shift all attributes (except midi channel) one TRACK number higher. Hold TRACK and turn [SPIN] to shift all STEPS forward or backward in that TRACK.  [REPT] allows the user to repeat the STEP or choose the number of rests on the STEP.  Positive values indicate repeats.  Negative values indicate rests (pauses). Hold STEP and turn [REPT] toward positive or negative values.  When a STEP is set to a negative repeat value it will play the contents of the STEP once and then rest for the duration of the number selected.  For example, -5 is placed on STEP 1 which results in STEP 1 playing contents of STEP once then rests on the STEP four times. Hold TRACK and text chnages to [MOVE]. This allows the user to move the TRACK steps forward or backward including the on/off state of steps.
column62: [NOTE] allows the user to adjust the pitch of a STEP or a TRACK.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [NOTE] to adjust pitch.  Notes can be adjusted as semitones or Hertz (this adds a pitchbend effect).  Click [NOTE] to toggle betwen the two. The default note setting for an unprogrammed STEP or TRACK is MIDI note #60 (middle C).
column63: [GATE] allows the user to program the length of a MIDI note on/off message. Hold a STEP and turn [GATE] to increase or decrease the length of a note by percentage in relation to the STEP.  For example, assume a STEP is four seconds long.  [GATE] is set at 50%.  This means that the note will play for two seconds.  If we increase the step to ten seconds in length our gate value will remain at 50% and the note will now play for five seconds.  The default value of a step toggled on is 50%.
column64: [VEL] represents loudness on a scale of 0 to 127.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and turn [VEL] to increase or decrease volume by increments of one. The default value of a STEP toggled on is 100. The LED becomes brighter to show an accent if VEL is adjusted over 120.
column65: [TIME] controls tempo. Turn [TIME] to set the global tempo in bpm.  Hold a TRACK and turn [TIME] to multiply or divide by the global tempo.  The user may also hold a STEP and turn [TIME] to multiply or divide by the global tempo.  Time changes global tempo when adjusted alone.
column67: [a/b] allows the user to toggle between two sequences. Click [a/b] to toggle between sequence "a" and sequence "b."   The first time the user clicks [a/b], sequence a copies to sequence b.  The text of the selected sequence appears bold on the display.  Hold [CQ] and click [a/b] to alternate play between sequence "a" and sequence "b." In this playback mode, the text of both sequence "a" and sequence "b" appears bold on the display.  There is also an additional playback mode "aaab."
column68: [Mute] silences a STEP or TRACK.  Hold [mute] and click a STEP or Track to silence it.  Hold [mute] and  [CQ] to invert muted and unmuted STEPS and TRACKS.  A muted STEP or TRACK appears RED.
column69: [Skip] prevents a STEP from playing in a TRACK.  Hold [skip] and click a STEP to prevent it from playing in the TRACK. LED is turned off for a skipped step
column70: [Clear] deletes information from a STEP or TRACK.  Hold [clear] and click a STEP or TRACK once to clear an EVENT and twice to clear all other attributes.
column72: [select] allows multiple tracks to be edited simultaneously.  Click [select] and all TRACKS light up by default.  User may toggle TRACKS in or out of the group selection by clicking the TRACK buttons.  TRACKS able to be edited appear illuminated.  Turn a knob or click a button to offset or affect illuminated TRACKS.  Hold [select] and click STEPS you want to edit.  Only those STEPS will illuminate orange to show you they are being edited.  Click a single STEP and all of its attributes will display on the OLED for editing.
column73: [Cue] allows the user to ready and store edits for future use. Click [cue] once and the LED flashes allowing the user to make edits to be executed later. Click [cue] once again and the LED appears solid while the edits are executed.  Click [cue] a third time to toggle [cue] off.  [Cue] appears dim if information is stored.  Hold [clear] and click [cue] to delete information in [cue]. Hold [CQ] and click [cue] to execute edits at the top leader's first STEP(aka end of loop, aka end of bar, aka next bar).
column75: [MRec] is a MIDI looper.  Hold [CQ] and click [Mrec] to begin recording (LED flashes). Turn knobs and click buttons to record these actions into the MRec Looper.  Click [MRec] to toggle recording off (LED lights solid) and the loop immediately plays back, each time the loop plays back the changes are cumulative.  Click [MRec] to toggle loop off (LED dims to show there is information stored but not playing back). When loop is toggled off all cumulative changes are destroyed.  ALTHOUGH use the copy feature at any time to capture the exact sequence to paste into an open slot. The user may overdub by recording again.  Hold [MRec] and click [clear] in order to delete the recorded loop.  Hold [MRec] and click a STEP in the grid to record for that many bars. When used this way information played back from the loop is not cumulative.
column76: [rec] allows the user to record data onto a TRACK.  Hold [rec] and click a TRACK to record internal or external MIDI data onto that TRACK.  The user must send data from the external devices to the same midi channel the TRACK(s) are set to transmit on.  The user may use internal keyboard area to enter notes in real time this way as well.  Hold [rec] and click a TRACK to arm that TRACK for recording.  Click [play] to allow that TRACK to record. The TRACK will record in real time as the user presses notes if the sequencer is running.
column77: [stop] pauses or resets the sequencer.  Click [stop] to pause the sequencer.  Click [stop] twice to reset the sequencer to STEP one and sends an all notes off message.
column78: Click [play] to play a sequence.  Click [play] while playing to align TRACKS.  For example, if the chase light of the leader is on STEP 3, all TRACKS will synchronize to STEP 3.  Hold a TRACK and click [play] to start or pause that TRACK immediately.
column80: This can be used to cursor to tracks when in analog mode.
column81: This can be used to cursor to tracks when in analog mode.
column82: This can be used to cursor to tracks when in analog mode.
column83: This can be used to cursor to tracks when in analog mode.
column85: [CQ] functions as a shift button on this instrument.  Hold [CQ] and click a STEP to lock all the parameters of that STEP.  While holding [CQ] the user may click knobs to toggle functions from the STEP lock.  STEP allows some attributes in the sequencer to remain the same. The value cannot be changed by modulation in STEP lock, it can only be changed by directly editing the STEP. [CQ] allows the user to de-select some features.  While held, some options on displays will change.
column86: [oct up] allows the user to shift a STEP or TRACK up one octave.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and click [oct up] to transpose the STEP or TRACK by 12 semitones.  Raises the keyboard pitch in increments of one octave when not engaged with a STEP or TRACK.
column87: [oct down] allows the user to shift a STEP or TRACK down one octave.  Hold a STEP or TRACK and click [oct down] to transpose the STEP or TRACK by 12 semitones.  Lowers the keyboard pitch in increments of one octave when not engaged with a STEP or TRACK.
column88: [KEYBOARD AREA] allows the user to place notes on STEPS, transpose tracks, and create scales (edit force to scale).  Hold a STEP and click a key on the keyboard to place that note on the same STEP.  The user may hold a TRACK and click a STEP to transpose a sequence that many semitones.  These keys can also be used to edit the scale.
column89: [scale] determines which notes are used during playback.   Click [scale] and its LED will glow solid to indicate [scale] is activated.  After the [scale] LED glows solid, click a specific TRACK or STEP to remove unwanted notes. As a result, incoming notes are forced to the closest note by frequency range.  For instance, if C and E are the only notes not turned off and the user inputs C#, C will play.Hold [CQ] and click [scale] and the LED will blink. The user may toggle notes off and apply these changes to the global scale.    Notes that are playable will remain lit up. Force to scale works for notes but not for octaves.  This means that notes will be removed from every octave.  Hold CQ and click [scale] and the scale LED will flash.  In this mode, every octave is programmable.  this is known as BDE scale.  scale limits notes.
column91: [cc] allows the user to assign Continuous Control messages to knobs and STEPS. When on the HOME screen, the user may use the top 16 knobs to to send CC messages to external synths/software.  Hold [cc] and turn knobs to change the MIDI CC of that knob. Click the knob to change the MIDI channel it is sending on.  Hold [cc] and click a TRACK to open the STEP GRID in order to draw shapes.  As the shape increases in height, the MIDI CC values will increase.  The top OLED display allows the user to select the CC  a track is sending information to.  The MIDI channel of a track determines the channel the CC is sent to.  Hold [cc] and click a STEP.  This triggers the MIDI CC number.  The MIDI CC value sent, however, is 0.  Holding [cc] and clicking a STEP sends a value of zero on the controller of that STEP.  This happens on STEPS 1-16.  This function is useful for synthesizers with MIDI Learn.  Hold [CQ] and click [cc] to open CC per-step edit mode. Use TRACK buttons to select a TRACK, use the 16 knob editor to place the CC controller and CC controller value on each STEP.  Clicking a knob of a STEP will toggle between CC and value.
column92: [focus] allows the user to look at or loop a pattern that is selected.  Click [focus] and its LED will glow solid.  The user may click on a pattern in order to only see this pattern although the chase light will continue moving.  Hold [CQ] and click [focus] (its LED will flash) and the sequencer will loop whatever the user is focusing on.  The user may click the right and left arrows to scroll through sequence numbers.
column93: [direct] allows the user to trigger STEPS by hand to play on the STEP GRID when the sequencer is stopped.  During playback, click a STEP to immediately play it.  Hold a STEP to continually play it until it is released.  Hold [CQ] and click [direct] to allow playback of a STEP from every TRACK.  For instance, with [CQ] engaged, the user may select STEP 2 from TRACK 2 and STEP 2 from every track will play.
column95: [home] allows the user to go to the home screen.  [home] LED flashes when the sequencer is not currently on the home screen.
column96: [piano] allows the user to toggle the STEP GRID into a piano roll editor in order to enter notes into TRACKS.  The user may click [piano] to turn [piano] mode on.  The user will notice the [piano] LED is illuminated and TRACK 1 is also illuminated.  The user will notice that there are two different colors for notes.  Each row in the sequencer from bottom to top will appear as a keyboard and notes will correspond from C4 to D#5.  Nested STEPS appear purple and the user may click on nested STEPS to zoom in.
column97: [analog] allows the user to edit TRACKS with the upper-right 16 knobs.  The user may click [analog] to turn [analog] mode on.  The user will notice the [analog] LED is illuminated.  Click a knob to turn a STEP off or on.  The 16 knob editor is ued and will allow the upper two displays change to show NOTE values for the 16 steps. These correlate to respective knobs.  User may turn knobs to edit pitch of each step. to change encoders to edit any other functions user may click encoders from the bottom two displays (NOTE, GATE, VELO, TIME, etc).  Click [left] or [right] to toggle the two bottom screens to reflect the attributes of the MidiFX screen(HRM1-3, STRM, ECHO, etc) and Event screen(NOTE, GATE, VELO, REP, etc).  In this mode, the lower group of knobs are used to select the attributes (NOTE, GATE, VELO, etc...) to edit. Click a knob of an attribute in order to select it for editing in the 16 knob editor
column98:
The 16 knob editor is located on the upper-right part of the sequencer. It inncludes the two upper displays and the upper sixteen knobs at the top of the sequencer.  
 The 16 knob editor can reflect either the sixteen TRACKS or STEPS during editing.  The knobs are read from left to right and correspond to 16 STEPS or TRACKS.  For instance, knob number five is the first knob on the second row of the 16 knob editor and it can correspond to TRACK five or STEP five.

The 16 knob editor can be used to control the following:  
1) analog mode STEPS
2) CC STEPS
3) Crossmod mode (emit/receive extended) STEPS
4) regen mode TRACKS
5) MIDI channel mode TRACKS
6) arpegiattor TRACKS
7) range TRACKS
8) remix mode TRACKS
9) direction mode TRACKS
10) song mode sequences

column21: EVENTS are per step changes that only modify the track they are placed on. they  occur every time the chaselight crosses the step. whether the step is toggled off or on
column22: NOTE EVENTS are cumulative and add or subtract in semitones to all steps in a track. example: if you put +4 on step 1 and -2 on step 9 the math would continue to happen every time the chase light passed over the steps
column23: GATE EVENTS are cumulative and add or subtract gate length in percentages to all steps in a track example: setting value to 10% will increase the gate length of every step in the track by 10% on each pass

column96: when this is engaged the grid becomes like a piano roll editor. the default is as follows:                                   tracks/rows 1-16 are equal to midi note numbers 60-75 (C4-D#5). white keys and black keys should be two different led colors.
column97: this is an edit mode that allows the user to turn the encoders to change values on steps of selected tracks.  when it opens the default is turning the encoder changes the note value, pushing the enoder toggles the step off and on. in order to change what the encoders are editing the user may select the attribute by engaging the touch screen and turning a knob. the encoder light to same color of track they are editing and the chaselight is reflected there as well.
column107: when a step is muted only the "note on/gate" is NOT generated. all other attributes ARE generated
